        "id": "101",
        "cd_name": "Extreme Make-Over (for Wind Orchestra)",
        "sub_title": "Metamorphoses on a Theme by Tchaikovsky",
        "composer": "Johan de Meij",
        "instrumentation": "wind orchestra",
        "synopsis": "<p>\\r\\n\t<em>Extreme Make-over </em>consists of a number of musical metamorphoses on a theme from Peter Ilyich Tchaikovsky&rsquo;s well-known <em>Andante cantabile</em> (the second movement of his String Quartet No. 1 in D, Op. 11, written in 1871). &ldquo;Never in my life have I felt so flattered, never have I been so proud of my creative powers as when Lev Tolstoy sat in the chair next to mine listening to my <em>Andante</em>, and the tears ran down his cheeks,&rdquo; wrote the composer in the winter of 1876 on the occasion of a special concert organised for Tolstoy at the Moscow Conservatory. In 1888 Tchaikovsky arranged this movement for cello and orchestra.<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\tThe main theme of the<em> Andante cantabile</em> is based on a Russian folksong. In <em>Extreme Make-over</em> this theme is introduced in its original form by a brass quartet consisting of two cornets, alto horn and euphonium. At the theme&rsquo;s reprise, muted cornets sneak, almost inaudibly, alongside the four soloists and elongate each note of the melody, as though the sustaining pedal on a piano has been depressed. The first metamorphosis emanates from a single tone, to which the two successive tones from the theme are added in bell-like chords. The addition of the lower second results in a completely new sound world, completing the first metamorphosis. Anticipating the canonic theme from the finale, a timpani solo forms the transition to the <em>Alla marcia</em>. This movement is composed in a robust neo-classical style and is peppered with quotes, including fragments from Tchaikovsky&rsquo;s Fourth and Sixth Symphonies and the Fantasy-Overture <em>Romeo and Juliet</em>.<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\tThe following movement features a rather unconventional instrumental group: ten tuned bottles, played by members of the cornet section. This group eventually provides the accompaniment for an extensive marimba solo, gradually producing a sort of gamelan effect. In composing for the tuned bottles I have applied the &lsquo;hoketus&rsquo; technique: each player produces a single note of the melody or the chord.<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\tThis fragile movement is joined seamlessly to the finale, a canonic treatment of the theme. Hurtling through each instrumental group, it leads us to a festive conclusion.<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\tJohan de Meij<br />\\r\\n\tAmsterdam, September 2004</p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\t<strong>Instrumentation</strong><br />\\r\\n\t1. Piccolo<br />\\r\\n\t4. Flutes I<br />\\r\\n\t4. Flutes II<br />\\r\\n\t1. Oboe I<br />\\r\\n\t1. Oboe II<br />\\r\\n\t1. English Horn (F)<br />\\r\\n\t1. Bassoon I<br />\\r\\n\t1. Bassoon II<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\t1. Eb Clarinet<br />\\r\\n\t6. Bb Clarinet I<br />\\r\\n\t6. Bb Clarinet II<br />\\r\\n\t6. Bb Clarinet III<br />\\r\\n\t1. Bb Bass Clarinet<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\t2. Eb Alto Sax I<br />\\r\\n\t2. Eb Alto Sax II<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Tenor Sax<br />\\r\\n\t1. Eb Baritone Sax<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\t2. F Horn I<br />\\r\\n\t2. F Horn II<br />\\r\\n\t2. F Horn III<br />\\r\\n\t2. F Horn IV<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Trumpet I<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Trumpet II<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Trumpet III<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Trumpet IV<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\t2. Trombone I (C)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Trombone II (C)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bass Trombone (C)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Baritone/Euphonium B.C. (C)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Baritone/Euphonium T.C. (Bb)<br />\\r\\n\t4. Basses (C)<br />\\r\\n\t1. String Bass<br />\\r\\n\t1. Piano<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\t1. Timpani<br />\\r\\n\t2. Marimba/Vibraphone<br />\\r\\n\t2. Tubular Bells/ Xylophone<br />\\r\\n\t4. Percussion</p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\t<strong>Additional Parts</strong><br />\\r\\n\t[for European countries only]<br />\\r\\n\t1. Eb Horn I<br />\\r\\n\t1. Eb Horn II<br />\\r\\n\t1. Eb Horn III<br />\\r\\n\t1. Eb Horn IV<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Trombone I (T.C. &amp; B.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Trombone II (T.C. &amp; B.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bass Bb Trombone (T.C. &amp; B.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Baritone/Euph. (B.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Eb Bass Tuba (T.C. &amp; B.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Bass Tuba (B.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t1. Bb Bass Tuba (T.C.)</p>\\r\\n",
