        "id": "39",
        "cd_name": "{{601}}''{{602}}",
        "sub_title": "{{603}}''{{604}}''{{605}}",
        "composer": "Giacomo Puccini/Arr. Johan de Meij",
        "instrumentation": "wind orchestra",
        "synopsis": "<p>\\r\\n\tGiacomo Puccini composed his first music theatre work, <em>Le Villi, </em>for the 1883 competition of one-act operas, issued by the publisher Sonzogno in the periodical <em>Il Teatro illustrato</em>. Puccini did not even earn an honourable mention with this work, probably because he had written the score in such a great hurry that it was hardly legible.</p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\tFor the hugely successful first performance of the work, Puccini received financial support by the librettist Arrigo Boito. Subsequently, the publisher Giulio Ricordi engaged Puccini, which proved to be a profitable move. &nbsp;Ricordi asked the composer to expand the work, so Puccini created a final version in 1892. It premiered in Hamburg the same year &shy;&ndash; by no less a conductor than Gustav Mahler.</p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\tThe poet Heinrich Heine once wrote the following about the fairy-like figures called &lsquo;Villi&rsquo; or &lsquo;Wilis&rsquo;: &ldquo;Wilis are betrothed maidens who died before their weddings. These poor creatures cannot find rest in their graves. &nbsp;In their dead hearts, in their dead feet, the passion for dancing lives on.&nbsp; A passion that they could not satisfy in their lifetime. At midnight they appear in groups along country lanes.&nbsp; Woe betide the young man who encounters them! He will be forced to dance with them, and he must dance until he drops dead!&rdquo;</p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\tPuccini wrote two movements for a symphonic intermezzo between the two acts &ndash; <em>L&#39;Abbandono</em> (The Desertion) and <em>La Tregenda</em> (The Witches&rsquo; Sabbath). The main character, Roberto, is bewitched and as a result forgets about his beloved Anna: She waits for the duration of three seasons, and finally dies in Roberto&rsquo;s absence. During the intermezzo, the legend of the &lsquo;Villi&rsquo; is explained: When a woman dies of a broken heart, the fairies force the heartbreaker to dance himself to death.&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n<p align=\"right\">\\r\\n\tAnthony Fiumara</p>\\r\\n",
