        "sub_title": "Overture for wind orchestra",
        "composer": "Johan de Meij",
        "instrumentation": "wind orchestra",
        "synopsis": "<p>\\r\\n\tThe overture recounts the magical re-awakening of spring&rsquo;s arrival in Sweden. After a long and dark winter, creatures great and small join Swedes desperately longing for the first rays of warming sunshine.</p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\tA melancholic, haunting song is first heard from afar (<em>N&auml;r som jag var p&aring; mitt adertonde &aring;r</em> &ndash; &lsquo;As I was on my 18th year&rsquo;). Various instruments from different locations in the concert hall are echoing the solitary female voice. The aching, soulful melody gradually transforms to a polka-like variant that builds to the joyful, optimistic Spring main theme. Creatures venture out from a long hibernation, people emerge from their homes to celebrate, and the main theme converts again into an even more jubilant, fast dance-like scene. At this point, another well-known Swedish folksong appears as a counter melody (<em>Ack V&auml;rmeland du sk&ouml;na</em> &ndash; &lsquo;Oh V&auml;rmland Thou Art Beautiful&rsquo;) thematically supporting the giddy celebrants. It is first introduced by a brass quartet (2 cornets, alto horn &amp; euphonium) and crescendos into the full, satisfying sounds of complete brass choir.<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\tJohan de Meij, December 2009<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\t<span style=\"font-size: 12px;\"><em>Notes on instrumentation and special effects:</em><br />\\r\\n\t* The locations of the female singer and the echoing instruments may vary, depending on the possibilities of the concert venue;<br />\\r\\n\t* If no alto horn is available, use a regular French horn [F]<br />\\r\\n\t* The use of wine glasses: tune glasses to concert pitch E-flat by adding or taking out water, and rub the rim with wet fingertip. Thin glasses or crystal glasses give the best result;<br />\\r\\n\t* Plastic hose: available in every toyshop. Swing around in the air to create sound; with a faster spin, the pitch will go up.</span></p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\t<strong>Instrumentation</strong><br />\\r\\n\t<em>Overture for Wind Orchestra [AM 113]</em><br />\\r\\n\t1. Piccolo (Flute 3)<br />\\r\\n\t8. Flutes 1, 2<br />\\r\\n\t2. Oboe 1, 2<br />\\r\\n\t1. English Horn (F)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bassoons 1, 2<br />\\r\\n\t1. Eb Clarinet<br />\\r\\n\t5. Bb Clarinet 1<br />\\r\\n\t5. Bb Clarinet 2<br />\\r\\n\t5. Bb Clarinet 3<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Bass Clarinet<br />\\r\\n\t2. Eb Alto Sax 1<br />\\r\\n\t2. Eb Alto Sax 2<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Tenor Sax<br />\\r\\n\t1. Eb Baritone Sax<br />\\r\\n\t1. Female Voice<br />\\r\\n\t3. F Horn 1, 3<br />\\r\\n\t3. F Horn 2, 4<br />\\r\\n\t4. Bb Cornet 1, 2<br />\\r\\n\t3. Bb Trumpet 1<br />\\r\\n\t3. Bb Trumpet 2<br />\\r\\n\t2. Trombone 1 (C)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Trombone 2 (C)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Trombone 3 (C)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Baritone/Euphonium B.C. (C)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Baritone/Euphonium T.C. (Bb)<br />\\r\\n\t4. Basses (C)<br />\\r\\n\t1. Double Bass<br />\\r\\n\t1. Harp<br />\\r\\n\t2. Mallets 1<br />\\r\\n\t2. Mallets 2<br />\\r\\n\t1. Timpani<br />\\r\\n\t4. Percussion 1, 2<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\t<strong>Additional Parts</strong> (for European countries only)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Eb Horn 1, 3<br />\\r\\n\t2. Eb Horn 2, 4<br />\\r\\n\t1. Bb Trombone 1 (T.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t1. Bb Trombone 2 (T.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t1. Bb Trombone 3 (T.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Baritone/Euph. (B.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t1. Eb Bass Tuba (T.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t1. Eb Bass Tuba (B.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t1. Bb Bass Tuba (T.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Bass Tuba (B.C.)</p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\t&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n",
