        "id": "94",
        "cd_name": "Magic Garden (from The Venetian Collection)",
        "sub_title": "",
        "composer": "Johan de Meij",
        "instrumentation": "wind orchestra",
        "synopsis": "<p>\\r\\n\t<em><strong>&ldquo;Painting turns space into time, music turns time into space&rdquo;</strong></em><br />\\r\\n\t[Hugo von Hofmannstal]<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\tMAGIC GARDEN by Johan de Meij was inspired by a painting of the same name [Zaubergarten, 1926] by German artist Paul Klee [1879 - 1940]. The work forms the third movement of THE VENETIAN COLLECTION, an orchestral suite in which De Meij gives his musical impressions of four different paintings from the Peggy Guggenheim Collection.<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\tPrecisely as the painting, the composition is completely different from the other parts of the cycle, which are all clearly exponents of Surrealism. De Meij aimed at illustrating Klee&rsquo;s colourful, naive dream world by means of a fragile, transparent texture, bringing extensively the woodwinds into the limelight. The rather abrupt conclusion is preceded by a breathtakingly fast unison passage for the complete woodwind group.<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\tMAGIC GARDEN was commissioned by the Hofstra University Symphonic Band from Hempstead, New York [USA].<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\tThe other movements of the THE VENETIAN COLLECTION are based on VOICE OF SPACE by Ren&eacute; Magritte, THE RED TOWER by Italian painter Giorgio De Chirico and EMPIRE OF LIGHT by, again, Ren&eacute; Magritte, who was a great admirer of De Chirico. All four paintings can be found in the Guggenheim Museum in Venice. Together with other outstanding museums in New-York, Bilbao and Berlin, this collection is part of the Solomon R. Guggenheim Foundation, one of the largest private art collections in the world.<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\tIn November 2000 THE RED TOWER was awarded the 1st Prize at the International Composition Contest of OMAN.</p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\t<strong>Instrumentation</strong><br />\\r\\n\t1. Piccolo<br />\\r\\n\t4. Flutes I<br />\\r\\n\t4. Flutes II<br />\\r\\n\t2. Oboes I/II<br />\\r\\n\t1. English Horn (F)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bassoons I/II<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\t1. Eb Clarinet<br />\\r\\n\t6. Bb Clarinet I<br />\\r\\n\t6. Bb Clarinet II<br />\\r\\n\t6. Bb Clarinet III<br />\\r\\n\t1. Eb Alto Clarinet<br />\\r\\n\t1. Bb Bass Clarinet<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\t1. Bb Soprano Sax<br />\\r\\n\t2. Eb Alto Sax I<br />\\r\\n\t2. Eb Alto Sax II<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Tenor Sax<br />\\r\\n\t1. Eb Baritone Sax<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\t3. F Horn I/III<br />\\r\\n\t3. F Horn II/IV<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Trumpet I<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Trumpet II<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Trumpet III<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Trumpet IV<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\t2. Trombone I (C)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Trombone II (C)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Trombone III (C)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Baritone/Euphonium B.C. (C)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Baritone/Euphonium T.C. (Bb)<br />\\r\\n\t4. Basses (C)<br />\\r\\n\t1. String Bass<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\t1. Timpani<br />\\r\\n\t4. Percussion I &amp; II &ndash; Glass Chimes, Snare Drum, Bass Drum, Tom-tom, Flexatone, Tam-tam, Triangle, Suspended Cymbal.<br />\\r\\n\t3. Mallets &ndash; Vibraphone, Marimba, Xylophone, Bells, Tubular Bells.<br />\\r\\n\t1. Piano<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\t<strong>Additional Parts</strong> [for European countries only]<br />\\r\\n\t2. Eb Horn I/III<br />\\r\\n\t2. Eb Horn II/IV<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Trombone I (T.C. &amp; B.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Trombone II&nbsp; (T.C. &amp; B.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Trombone III&nbsp; (T.C. &amp; B.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Bb Baritone/Euph. (B.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t2. Eb Bass Tuba&nbsp; (T.C. &amp; B.C.)<br />\\r\\n\t3. Bb Bass Tuba (T.C. &amp; B.C.)&nbsp;</p>\\r\\n",
