        "composer": "Gustav Holst / arr. Johan de Meij ",
        "instrumentation": "wind orchestra / fanfare",
        "synopsis": "<p>\\r\\n\tJust like his friend and fellow composer Ralph Vaughan Williams, Gustav Holst (1874-1934 ) had a strong preference for the abundant folk music of the British Isles, which is particularly noticeable in his &ldquo;Second Suite&rdquo; (in F) for Military Band&nbsp; (1922)&nbsp; but also in his &ldquo;St. Paul&rsquo;s Suite&rdquo;&nbsp; for string orchestra. This opus was completed in 1913 and was especially composed for the school orchestra of St. Paul&rsquo;s Girls&rsquo; School in the London borough of Hammersmith, where Holst was appointed Director of Music in 1905, a post he was to hold until his death in 1934. It is striking that Holst was to orchestrate the last part of this suite, &ldquo;Fantasia on the Dargason&rdquo; (in which the &lsquo;Greensleeves&rsquo; theme is ingeniously dealt with) anew as the finale for his &ldquo;Second Suite&rdquo;.</p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\tThe &ldquo;St. Paul&rsquo;s Suite&rdquo; opens with an exuberant &ldquo;Jig&rdquo;, a dance originating from Scottish and Irish folk music in alternating duple and triple time (mostly 6/8 and 9/8), sometimes called &ldquo;Gigue&rdquo;.<br />\\r\\n\t<br />\\r\\n\tAlso available in the &lsquo;AMSTEL CLASSICS&rsquo; series: (AM 09) Gustav Holst / Johan de Meij &ldquo;Jupiter Hymn&rdquo; from &ldquo;The Planets&rdquo; (1914-1917). Separate instrumentation for Fanfare Band (AM 10)</p>\\r\\n",
