        "id": "1074",
        "cd_name": "Echoes of San Marco",
        "sub_title": "",
        "composer": "Johan de Meij",
        "instrumentation": "Wind Orchestra",
        "synopsis": "<p>\\r\\n\tClick <a href=\"https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=5em33-hKn90\">HERE</a> to listen &amp; watch the score with SCOREPLAY.</p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\t<strong>Echoes of San Marco &ndash; Johan de Meij (Winner of the 30th Edition of the International Composition Competition in Corciano &ndash; Italy.)<br />\\r\\n\t</strong><em>(for wind orchestra)</em></p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\t<em>Echoes of San Marco</em> was composed as homage to Italian composer <em>Giovanni Gabrieli&nbsp;</em>(1554 &ndash; 1612), the renaissance maestro who was well known for his use of double wind ensembles, mirroring each other sonically in the awe-inspiring San Marco Cathedral in Venice, Italy. Majestic brass fanfares from two different locations in the back of the concert hall mark the opening of the work: we hear fragments from Giovanni Gabrieli&rsquo;s majestic&nbsp;<em>Canzon Septimi Toni a 8&nbsp;</em>from the&nbsp;<em>Sacrae Symphoniae</em>&nbsp;(1597), originally written for two four-part brass choirs. Several groups within the orchestra, such as a double-reed choir,&nbsp;a saxophone quartet, a horn quartet, euphonium/tuba quartet and two sets of tubular bells&nbsp;mimic&nbsp;the brass choirs,&nbsp;while&nbsp;the clarinet choir and a flute quartet prolong the echoes with mysterious cluster chords. New thematic material is developed out of one of the bass lines of the opening section, quoting a four-note motif C-A-D-G. The work&nbsp;reaches&nbsp;a&nbsp;triumphant conclusion with a grand hymn.</p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\t&ldquo;Echoes of San Marco&rdquo; is the winner of the 30th Edition of the International Composition Competition in Corciano &ndash; Italy. The Jury praised the work for its &lsquo;highly original writing and inventive orchestrations&rsquo;. It is the fourth time that De Meij has been awarded in this prestigious competition.&nbsp; In 1995, he received the honourable mention for his Symphony No. 2 &ldquo;The Big Apple&rdquo;. In 1999, he took1<sup>st</sup> prize for his cello concerto &ldquo;Casanova&rdquo;. He was awarded 2<sup>nd</sup> prize for Symphony No. 3 &ldquo;Planet Earth&rdquo; in 2006.</p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\t<em>Echoes of San Marco</em> was commissioned by Col. Larry H. Lang, Commander of the United States Air Force Band to commemorate its 75<sup>th</sup> Anniversary in 2016.</p>\\r\\n<p>\\r\\n\t<em>Performance suggestions</em><br />\\r\\n\tThe two brass quartets need to be placed in the back of the hall in the two corners, ideally on a balcony if there is one. The horn quartet and saxophone quartet can be placed backstage left and right, or on a front balcony, depending on the venue. <em>Echoes of San Marco</em> would work wonderful in a church or cathedral with rich acoustics, to emphasize the echo effects throughout the work.</p>\\r\\n",
